~Rose <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ilharessviviennelileath>Ilharess Vivienne Lileath</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/8/03 5:21 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm49.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=31.topic&index=72>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://members.shaw.ca/baddog117/vivieyes.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Side note</span><hr size=1> Ever since Vivienne's creation, she has been agnostic, she despises Innoruuk and pays him only lipservice for appearances to the Lodge of Dead. Since becoming part of the Coven, she has begun to bid for blessings from the White Mother and Dark Father - Tunare and Innoruuk perhaps? - but she does NOT view them as seperate entities, more like aspects of the same being and not even really gods, more a force of thought and ideals. Any ways, my point is, I have yet to encounter somebody that has issue with this in any real RP sense. Nobody has said to me. &quot;what? you can't be an agnostic necromancer&quot; &lt;shrugs&gt;<br>
<br>
I have not played Vivienne viewing herself as evil, she has more depth to her than that. She is cruel, yes, capable of committing some of the most terrifying crimes and acts of perversion, but is also capable of incredilble love and devotion, even going to far as to sacrifice herself so those she loves are not put in danger. Some have called her nice and pleasant, others a nasty bitch. Some have even called her good, others have commented that she gives them chills IRL ( &lt;hugs&gt; to the Clan of Brothers member who said that, I love you for it &lt;giggles&gt; )<br>
<br>
I guess my biggest issue is the views of good and evil... true they are RP guidelines... but that is all, just guidelines, not a straightjacket. In our RL, do we classify ourselves as good and evil? Do we wake up one morning and realize &quot;hey, I am Neutral Good&quot;? No, we don't, so why would our characters? I would never have Vivienne join a &quot;good&quot; guild... why? Because she would not look to them as accepting of her magick and powers, not because their charter says &quot;good aligned&quot; only. Just the same as a paladin trying to join one of the &quot;evils&quot;, they would not find acceptance for their life choice and personality.<br>
<br>
Bakanome has a point though, a fallen high elf paladin would not work, in my opinion, simply because their powers supposedly come from Tunare UNLESS the paladin was in a struggle to redeem themselves - now that would be an interesting character to RP - one with dark thoughts and desire to destroy, but the whispers of their loving mother goddess always in their head, trying to bring them back to the path of righteousness.<br>
<br>
Same idea with a wizard of Solusek Ro ( I am not too familiar with the god and don't have our EQ RPG book handy, but he sounds neutral from others' talk of him ). Fire is a neutral element, but it can be a force of both cleansing good and destructive evil.<br>
<br>
Again, do we fall into the race/class/diety straightjacket? or do we go beyond that? I, for one, would much rather RP with the struggling paladin ( and if I was the leader of a dark guild, go so far as to try and invite them in to further drag them down ) than a cookie-cutter &quot;evil&quot; dark elf or troll. &lt;shrugs&gt; but, that is just my opinion &lt;giggles and waves&gt;<br>
<br>
P.S. as to the cookie-cutter remark, I was not attempting to bash anybody, the dark Innoruuk-loving teir'dal is the norm for the society, just meant to illustrate that somebody shouldn't be punished, but instead embraced, for breaking the norm if their character concept actually has an interesting background and story. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://members.shaw.ca/baddog117/vivirose.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=eliezeroferudin>Eliezer of Erudin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/8/03 5:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm49.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=31.topic&index=73>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Drama</span><hr size=1> Fajon, you are absolutely correct.  BUT.... (and there is always a but) that is NOT what a lot of Guilds are doing.<br>
<br>
The Legion of Cornhuskers doesn't say we only allow X, Y, and Z - They say we only allow Evil (or Good).  Then in the fine print they define what Evil and Good are.  This invariably causes the argument &quot;But I am Evil/Good too!  It's not fair you disregard my Roleplay!&quot;<br>
<br>
An All Tier'dal Guild probably won't have problems with Evil Halflings pestering them to join, it's the Guilds that choose to define Good and Evil that will butt heads with people whose definitions differ. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=syllestraefv>Syllestrae FV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderating inconsistently<br>since Jun 2002</span><br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/8/03 5:30 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm49.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=31.topic&index=74>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Drama</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>An All Tier'dal Guild probably won't have problems with Evil Halflings pestering them to join<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
